<p>[29 August]</p>
<p>took on mails also sent us some papers &ndash; very welcome.</p>
<p>The Flagship with the "Melbourne" is at Samoa, where she convoyed an expedition from New Zealand to take the place. The "Aldenham" has been chartered as a store ship.</p>
<p>We arrived at Palm Ids 5pm Tues. and then found "Encounter" and "Berrima" troopship. These islands are inside the Barrier and about 10 miles off the coast. On a whole they are rather pretty, being hilly and thickly covered with foliage. I shall say there were about five of them. I landed one day and called a farm &ndash; Bullers, to get milk, and any other supplies &ndash; We got milk and a suckling pig but nothing else except some flowers. The man had been there 14 yrs and said he made a tolerable living. His produce, of a mixed mature, was sent to Townsville by steam each week.</p>
<p>We were lying in the roadstead for several days, nothing particular happening except of exchange of visits between ships. Troops were landed frequently for exercise and practice.</p>
